The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Sunday, March 06, 2005 

 BRIEFS

 Singur, March 5: A wireless set was stolen from a police jeep in Singur police station, about 40 km from Calcutta, in Hooghly on Tuesday. 

 The wireless set fitted in a police jeep was stolen when the vehicle was parked inside the police station. Senior district police officials suspect involvement of their own men in the theft. The additional superintendent of police, Asit Pal said a departmental inquiry had been ordered, but no one was arrested. The theft was kept a secret for three days and disclosed today. 

 Siliguri: Blaming the Nepal monarchy for the Maoist insurgency, state minister for urban development and municipal affairs Asok Bhattacharya has called for restoration of democracy in the kingdom. ?There was a constitutionally appointed Prime Minister, but he was given limited powers.... Therefore King Gyanendra?s dismissal of the government on charges of not being able to tackle the Maoist problem is unjustified,? he said.

 Bongaon: Border Security Force jawans on Saturday detained two women who were carrying heroin in huge quantities. The women, one identified as Nilofur Begum, were detained at the Haridaspur-Jayantipur border, about 80 km from Calcutta. BSF sources said the two were trying to enter India and were detained initially for entering without valid papers. Later, the jawans found they were carrying heroin worth several lakhs of rupees with them.

 Calcutta: Finance minister Asim Dasgupta will place the state budget in the Assembly on March 21, Speaker Hashim Abdul Halim informed on Friday. He said the budget session of the Assembly will begin on March 10 and continue till March 31. Eight bills will be placed in the session, he said. 

 Calcutta: A reception was organised for the President of Venezuela Hugo Chavez here on Saturday. The function was held at Rabindra Sarovar stadium where Chavez drove in straight from the airport. He was in Delhi earlier. Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee and governor Gopal Krishna Gandhi were present.




